he Ignorabimusstreit. Schopenhauer and Wilhelm Dilthey play important roles in these controversies but so do many neglected figures, including Ludwig Büchner, Eugen Dühring, Eduard von Hartmann, Julius Fraunstaedt, Hermann Lotze, Adolf Trendelenburg, and two women, Agnes Taubert and Olga Pluemacher, who have been completely forgotten in histories of philosophy. The result is a wide-ranging, original, and surprising new account of German philosophy in the critical period between Hegel and the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aPhilosophy, Germany19th century. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh  aAdolf Trendelenburg.  aArthur Schopenhauer.  aClio.  aEduard von Hartmann.  aEmil Du Bois-Reymond.  aEugen Dhring.  aGerman philosophy.  aHegel.  aLudwig Bchner.  aPessimismusstreit.  aPhilosophie des Unbewussten.  aRomanticism.  aWilhelm Dilthey.  aautonomy.  aconsciousness.  afaith.  ahistory.  aidealism.  amaterialism controversy.  amaterialism.  amatter.  ametaphysics.  amind.  amodern natural science.  amodern philosophy.  aneo-Kantian ideal.  anineteenth century.  aobjectivity.  apessimism.  aphilosophia perennis.  apositivism.  arealism.  areason.  ascience.  ascientific knowledge.  ascientific materialism.  aworldview.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066592540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400852536zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400852536423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400852536.jpg  a978-3-11-066592-5  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTL